on/off mild headache; extreme fatigue; swollen, very tender pea size lymph node by collarbone nearest to the injection site; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse (patient herself). A 26-year-old female patient received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection, lot number: EK5730; expiry date: unknown) via an unspecified route of administration (arm left), on 18Dec2020 at 10:45, at a single dose, for COVID-19 immunization. Patient is not pregnant at the time of vaccination. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. COVID-19 vaccine was administered in the hospital. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. Relevant medical history included attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), anxiety, chronic back pain, and allergies to penicillin. Concomitant medications included ethinylestradiol, ferrous fumarate, norethisterone acetate (JUNEL FE), amfetamine aspartate, amfetamine sulfate, dexamfetamine saccharate, dexamfetamine sulfate (ADDERALL), baclofen, oxymetazoline hydrochloride (CLARITIN ALLERGIC), and sertraline hydrochloride (ZOLOFT). On 19Dec2020, 24hrs post vaccination, the patient had a swollen, very tender pea size lymph node by collarbone nearest to the injection site, and an on/off mild headache. 48hrs post vaccination, patient had extreme fatigue and on/off headache, still had swollen lymph nodes. The patient did not receive treatment for the events. Outcome of the event swollen lymph nodes was not recovered, while for the other events was unknown. Since the vaccination, has the patient has not been tested for COVID-19.

Close
On 01/07/2021 I woke up at 0300am with chills, headache, body aches, joint pain, fever of 101.2 and swollen left axillary lymph nodes. I took Tylenol and Benadryl and it relieved the fever/headache/body aches/joint pain, however the lymph nodes in my left axillary remained swollen. I continue to take Tylenol for the fever/body aches/pains without relief for the swollen and painful axillary lymph nodes. Warm compresses do help to relieve the pain temporarily but they remain painfully swollen. On 01/08/21 I called my doctors office to ask if it was normal to experience such painfully swollen axillary lymph nodes to which they stated ?we don?t know, it is too soon for us to tell what?s normal and what isn?t normal right now.? They did not offer any suggestions to relieve the pain or swelling. The morning of 01/09/2021 , I called Employee Health at my hospital (my place of work and also where I received the vaccine) and they also stated they didn?t know if this was a normal reaction due to the newness of the vaccine. A couple hours later, employee health emailed me a link to the VAERS reporting website and asked me to file a report.

26 2021-01-14 swelling Patient developed angioedema of her eyelids after COVID-19 vaccination. She received her Covid vacc... Read more
Close
Patient developed angioedema of her eyelids after COVID-19 vaccination. She received her Covid vaccine on 1/10/2021 at 11:30 AM. She received the Pfizer vaccine. She works at a nursing home. She had some fatigue and tiredness during the day but woke up on the second day without any symptoms. On 1/30/2021, she developed bilateral eyelid swelling. The swelling is mild to moderate intensity involving the upper and lower eyelids bilaterally with a prickly burning sensation associated with pruritus. The reaction lasted less than a day and resolved without any skin desquamation, scarring or bruising. She denies any hives anywhere else. She does not have a large local reaction at the injection site. She denies respiratory complaints, GI symptoms, lightheadedness, loss of consciousness, wheezing, swelling of her throat or other symptoms consistent with anaphylaxis. She used Benadryl with significant improvement. She had a significant reaction after influenza vaccination consisting of swelling of her face and her eyelids with development of dry patches bilaterally within 2 days, resolving with skin desquamation. The reaction lasted for 1 week. She received her influenza vaccination in October 20, 2020. She was seen in our office in 2012 for bilateral eyelid angioedema with associated urticaria shortly after swimming in the pool. She was given oral antihistamines ?Zyrtec once daily? with significant improvement as well as prevention of this reaction. She has not had this reaction for more than 6 years.

Blisters around hips, thighs, and elbows.; Intermittent chest pain and tightness; Intermittent chest pain and tightness; shortness of breath; Swollen lymph nodes under bilateral arms that have not decreased; Chills; sweating; Headache; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse (patient). A 26-year-old female patient (not pregnant) received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Solution for injection, lot number= ELO140), via an unspecified route of administration at left arm on 14Jan2021 12:00 at single dose for covid-19 immunization. Medical history included known allergies: cephalosporins, coconut. Other medical history was none. There were no concomitant medications. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. On 15Jan2021 at time of 05:00 AM, the patient experienced blisters around hips, thighs, and elbows; Intermittent chest pain and tightness with shortness of breath beginning one day after vaccine and continuing into day 4 DOST vaccine, swollen lymph nodes under bilateral arms that had not decreased, chills and sweating, headache. No treatment received for the events. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures post vaccination which included COVID nasal swab test and COVID PCR test, both were negative on 14Jan2021. The outcome of events was not recovered.; Sender's Comments: The reported blisters around hips, thighs, and elbows; Intermittent chest pain and tightness with shortness of breath beginning one day after vaccine was probably related to the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) due to temporal relationship. The case will be reassessed should additional information become available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Approximately 20 hours after injection (about 7pm) I had some common symptoms. I began to develop a mild fever of 100.3, body aches, headache, swollen arm. These persisted throughout the night. I treated with Tylenol as recommended. I got a LOT of sleep and fever and headache persisted until about noon the next day. By 4pm I was feeling good again except my lymph nodes under my left arm are swollen and are tender and painful. I am treating the swollen lymph node pain with Tylenol. Over all the fever only lasted less than 24 hours with plenty of sleep. It also is worth noting that my first dose I had zero side effects. These side effects from the second dose seem harmless enough and tolerable as they don't last long.

On 2/3/2021 I woke up with pain, swelling, redness, and decreased range of motion in my R elbow at the site where I had hardware (wires, pins, tension band) placed during a surgical repair of my olecranon process in 2013. I have never had any issues with this elbow since the surgery, and no illnesses/dental work/medication changes in the months before this. The only change was getting my COVID vaccine. I went to see my PCP Dr. who advised me to go to the ER due to fear of a potential infection based on these symptoms. I went to the ER and after extensive testing they ruled out this being an infectious cause, though I was put on PO doxycycline as a precaution. An orthopedic specialist came to see me and determined that my body is essentially rejecting the hardware and I need to have surgery to have it removed. Since then, the swelling has decreased, however I still have persistent pain in my elbow along the site where the hardware is inserted and limited mobility due to pain with certain movements that put tension on this joint. I will need to have surgery eventually to have the hardware removed but am hoping to wait a couple months so that I can complete nursing school. I was advised to report any potential side effects from this vaccine and am choosing to do so as I do not know of any other reason this could be happening.

My fever got higher and higher and I felt worse and worse. My fever got over 104 degrees when my fever reducers were wearing off. I had no fever on Thursday, but I had the worst neck pain and migraine of my life for the next 3 days going from a sitting to standing position made me feel like my head was going to split into 2 and I verbally screamed a couple times from the head pain because it was such a searing pain that I have never experienced. My neck was so swollen and sore that I felt like I couldn't hold my head up. I never feel like I fully recovered from getting sick. I have not experienced fatigue like this since I got mono when I was 19, I take 3-4 hour naps after work everyday because I barely have enough energy to stay up for my shifts let alone get through a whole day. I am running shorter distances and slower miles and I can not run without napping first and my knees hurt when I walk/run/ and when on my feet at work. I have never experienced knee pain before I got sick from the vaccine and now it won't go away.

26 2021-04-26 lymph node swelling Shot received at 7pm on the 23rd (Fri). I felt a little giddy, likely due to the emotional impact of... Read more
Close
Shot received at 7pm on the 23rd (Fri). I felt a little giddy, likely due to the emotional impact of excitement for treatment (this happened to me with my first shot, and both times with my partner). Experienced what I felt was like feeling mentally a little 'out of it' a few hours in, maybe late that night 10-12pm. I did not have notable physical symptoms until exactly 12 hours after injection. Around 7-8AM I was woken up with body aches. I spent most of that day (Sat) taking ibuprofen and hydrating a lot. I had a small fever that peaked at 100.00 F after chills, etc, once this broke I mostly felt better. Sunday I had some minor aches. It is now Tuesday and here is the reason I am writing this report: I have had very low appetite since getting the shot, but I have pre-existing GI issues. This also happened on the first shot. Both times I have also had slight lymph swelling (mostly on first shot, and it was on the side of my body where injection was given, notably in the armpit, but possibly groin or shoulder). The only thing that has honestly caused me concern is my mental health: I have pre-existing psychiatric diagnoses and some extenuating circumstances (recent death in the family, needing to travel, job loss, pandemic, on top of major depression and PTSD) however I felt that my threshold for coping with day to day stuff has been blunted since getting the vaccine. It is manageable and I do think that it will go away as it did with the first shot. I felt like the last few days have been akin to "PMSing", ie; irritable, crying a lot. Contextually, there are reasons for me to be having emotional fluctuations, but I have therapy and have been off/on medications safely and usually have this fairly under control. The reason it was bothering me is I felt that if this happened to other people who had less support or managed diagnoses or other circumstances, it could be worse for them. My partner (who is BP2) has also felt a little more emotionally unstable than usual. We do not think this is from the psychological toll solely of vaccination, the pandemic, or reopening, as it seems to be unrelated to this. Sure, this is anecdotal, but I think it may be important, especially in the event of someone who could have psychotic or mood swing issues (ie: BP1 or schizophrenia, etc). Again, anecdotal, but on some online forums a lot of people have reported having similar mood instability when theirs was otherwise manageable (and these were people who were pro-vax, pro-science, etc). I am worried that if there is not a warning in the future, more people could pre-emptively have mental health adverse effects and not know why. I think it is very seriously from the vaccine. For me this mostly included appetite issues, insomnia (especially the night after I got the shot), crying more, irritability, feeling kind of "flat", etc. Perhaps this is just due to the body fighting and doing it's job. I felt however it would be irresponsible of me not to report it. I have spoken with my mental health provider about this and do not find that I need further treatment but that I wanted them to know, and that I wanted to file a VAERS report additionally to help the study of the vaccine in case this happens to others.

26 2021-05-15 peripheral swelling It started with back of knee pain that made it difficult for me to walk. I went to an urgent care on... Read more
Close
It started with back of knee pain that made it difficult for me to walk. I went to an urgent care on 4/12 and I was given a steroid for my leg inflammation. When the pain didn't subside two days later, I went to the ER and was admitted. It did not feel like I had muscle weakness. It felt like there were long rubber bands in my legs that felt tight and were about to snap. I also began to develop sensitivity to light touch (loose sweatpants moving against my legs while walking would cause pain up and down my legs). It has gotten easier to walk as time has gone on, and now instead of two large rubber bands feeling tight in my legs, it feels like there are many tiny, tight strings running up and down my legs.Sometimes if I walk too much or overextend my legs, these strings feel like they're on fire. Recently, my arms and different parts of my body have felt light burning intermittently throughout the day. My hands also felt like they were very hot yesterday (5/8) evening. When I looked at my hands, they looked a bit red/swollen with a tinge of blue/purple coloring. Fingers felt tender when typing, though I saw no sign of bruising. A few days ago, when I would hold up my phone to text, within a few seconds, my arms and hands felt like they were falling asleep. My right arm appeared to be worse that my left (it would fall asleep faster). The feeling in my arms would return when I would put my hands to my sides. This has never happened to me before. I have tried using my hands less and tried being more gentle with them. As a result, my arms and hands feel better after periods of rest/light use, but if I start using my arms/hands more regularly, the falling asleep sensation returns. I have also noticed more skin sensitivity as of late. I stopped wearing pants to prevent from feeling the leg pain I had mentioned earlier in this message. However, I was walking around the house yesterday (5/8) only wearing underwear, and I started to feel some light pain around the band of my underwear. I removed it and the pain went away. In addition, I normally wear loose t-shirts, but recently I had been experiencing a burning in my back/spine area. Once I removed my shirt, the burning sensation stopped. Wrists have also been feeling a bit stiff/achy as of late. Today (5/9) I was typing for about 30 to 45 minutes while working on this document. My fingertips felt tender, but I thought that I could use my hands for a bit without issue. I positioned myself so that my hands were below my body for constant blood supply. However, my right hand ring finger started to hurt and made it hard for me to type, so I have been resting on and off while working on this. It was a sharp string pain running along my finger. I checked both hands and they were red/swollen. Similar to this, on 5/2, I felt left middle finger pain that came and went over the span of a few days. I have not felt this left middle finger pain as of late. When I was in the ER (around 4/17), I felt left foot toe pain in the toe that's next to the pinky. The toe pain and finger pain were similar to each other in the sense that it was a sharp string pain. The working theory from the ER is that the vaccine might be causing flare ups for different ailments that I have had or am currently experiencing. I had injured the back of my left knee while in college, I had twisted the toe that started to feel pain while in the ER a few years back, I've had hemorrhoids before, but they've usually been painless and not noticeable. However, around the same time that it became harder for me to walk, my hemorrhoid pain became excruciating and now I have multiple hemorrhoids. I was tentatively diagnosed with potential reactive rheumatoid arthritis as a result of the Pfizer covid-19 vaccine. The latest development in this string of occurrences is that as of this morning (5/16/2021), I've had some brain fog that has lasted me the entire day. In addition, I have a dull, achy pain stemming from my right shoulder-blade to my right elbow that I've been experiencing for a few hours now. My hearing has also been feeling more sensitive for this past week now. I noticed this starting from about 5/8. One of my friends was talking to me, and whenever she spoke, her voice sounded a bit fuzzy from my right ear and I could feel the vibrations in my right ear when she talked. The next day, my phone pinged, and similar to my experience with my friend, it sounded fuzzy in my right ear, plus I could feel my eardrum vibrating. Usually, I'm quite hard of hearing and putting things on the highest volume isn't enough for me, but now, putting things at regular volume can seem a little too loud for me at times.

I don't know if this is an adverse event, but I wanted to report symptoms I'm experiencing. 2 days after receiving the second injection for the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine, I noticed a tender lump above my collarbone on the left side; the lump was not immediately visible, but I could feel it with my fingers and move it around. After examining the site of the lump, it appeared to be swollen when compared to my collarbone on the right side. The lump on the left side is the same side I received the injection. After researching, it appears that the tender lump may be a swollen lymph node(s) near my collar bone related to the Pfizer vaccine. It has now been present for 5 days, but appears to be reducing in size and sensitivity as time goes on. I have contacted my primary care provider who has instructed me to monitor the lump and follow up in person after a few weeks if it has not subsided.

Woke with up chest, arm and jaw pain on 03/21/2021. Presented to the ED. Her initial EKG was negative for any acute changes but her troponin was elevated. Cardiology was consulted. Her echo was negative for cardiomyopathy or hypertrophy. But after her troponin continued to rise she was taken to the cath lab to look for ischemia. Her cardiac angiography was negative for obstructive disease, and coronary arteries were completely normal. Had low magnesium and potassium- so started on oral supplementation. Discharged on 03/22/2021 with nitroglycerin (which was not helpful and made her feel worse/nauseated) and to follow up with outpatient cardiac MRI and cardiology. This imaging revealed significant myocardial edema consistent with myocarditis. 04/01/2021 Per Cardiology: -Given that the patient had covid 19 back in November 2019 I believe she may have had a low yield subacute myocardial infection at that time that was somehow exacerbated by her 1st covid vaccine. Therefore, after some consideration and careful discussion I am advising against the 2nd vaccine at this time. -No physical exercise for 6 months given her current myocarditis and family hx of sudden cardiac death -May trial PRN NSAIDS for pain relief -Recommend birth control and no pregnancy until at least after her follow up cMRI -Follow up in 6 months with cMRI prior

28 2021-03-13 anaphylactic shock Symptoms: Fainting, Unconciouness (repeatedly), Profusive Sweating, Low Blood Pressure (60 over unkn... Read more
Close
Symptoms: Fainting, Unconciouness (repeatedly), Profusive Sweating, Low Blood Pressure (60 over unknown number), Nausea, Dizziness, Unable to stabilize quickly, not able to get an IV, extreme thirst Signs: Immediately felt unwell within 5 minutes of the vaccine. Time Course: Injection (1st dose - Pfizer) at 4:00pm. Adverse Reaction at 4:05/4:10 (est.) Released at 5:00pm (est.) Description of Incident: On March 8th, at 4:00 pm, I received my first dose of the covid vaccine. Within 5 to 7 minutes, I felt unwell while sitting in the waiting area. I walked towards a worker to inform them that I was feeling unwell and that I was going to pass out. I became unresponsive and laid on the ground. My husband was with me at the time. I was unconscious for a bit and when I regained consciousness, my legs were being raised. I regained consciousness and was able to recall my name, DOB, and address. After I was done recalling my information, I began to lose consciousness again. They brought a wheelchair and took me to the medical room. As I moved from the wheelchair to the bed, I began to lose consciousness again. They told me to lay down. I overheard a woman ask my husband if I had diabetes or heart problems. He answered ?No.?. She explained to him that my body did not know how to accept the vaccine and was trying to regulate back to normal. She explained that my body was going through ?homeostasis? (?). While I laid on the bed, some workers took my blood pressure and tried to start an IV. One of them made a comment and said I was extremely dehydrated. This was odd to hear because I normally drink 3 to 4 liters of water daily. During this entire medical event, I felt the water pushing out through my pores. I was drenched in sweat. He tried to start an IV on my left arm and was unsuccessful. He tried to start an IV on my right hand, which was also unsuccessful. He stated they were unable to start IV liquids because my veins kept popping/collapsing. My blood pressure was reading 60. They checked it again, still at 60. I laid in the bed and basically waited it out. After a few minutes, they checked my blood pressure at it was at 120. They said that was good and I was good to go. No report was given to me nor my husband about the event that occurred. Even after they agreed to let me use a wheelchair (due to feeling weak), one was not provided to me. They basically stated that I was ?good to go?, after doing a series of hand squeezes and walking a few steps upright. I am currently trying to obtain a copy of the report I saw the gentleman fill out at the time. I was given Zofran to help with my nausea, it was placed under my tongue. After going home, I felt weak, tired and somewhat lightheaded. My husband drove me home and I got some rest. I set an appointment with my doctor on Friday March 12th to determine what happened to me during my vaccine and to record the incident. After describing the incident, she determined that it was anaphylaxis. She recommended for me not to get my second dose due to the anaphylactic shock I experienced with the first dose. She was shocked to learn that they did not transport me to the hospital or provided an Epi Pen injection. When asked why I didn?t drive myself to the hospital, I let her know that they told me I was ?good?. They did not explain what had occurred to me, no mention of anaphylaxis was explained. I was not aware that is what had occurred. The incident occurred from 4:00pm (injection time) to 5:00pm (left location).

My spine in my upper back began to feel bruised, along with my sternum which feels bruised and inflamed internally. I've been so uncomfortable that I've been having trouble sleeping. The pain also worsens after I eat, which makes eating really difficult. I made a second doctor's appointment for today, April 17th, 2021 (I was unable to get a sooner appointment) . My doctor confirmed that the rash is in fact Shingles and she prescribed me Valtrex and Percocet for the pain. I am currently taking these medications. Because I just found out my diagnosis today, I am still in severe pain and it's been 14 days since my second Pfizer vaccine. I do not have any known autoimmune disorders.

The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Flares only last about 24-36 hours now and will go away without medication but it does clear faster with hydrocortisone and antihistamines. The rash only flares at night, and no triggers like heat, alcohol or certain foods seem to bring it out. I have been consistently taking famotidine and cetirizine daily since the last flare of the rash, and have not experienced a flare again yet.

Vaccine given on Friday 1/8 at 10am. Started having significant fevers, chills, myalgias, rigors on 1/9 around 1pm. Symptoms lasted for about 8hrs. On 1/10 developed left upper arm, axillary, chest wall, and clavicular soft tissue swelling with significant lymphadenopathy. Lymphadenopathy was tender, multiple nodes ~2cm. Started experiencing severe sharp shooting pain and burning in similar region. On 1/11 started developing weakness in L arm and hand, with numbness in left hand. Went to urgent care on 1/11. Exam demonstrated 4/5 strength of left arm and hand. Started prednisone 40mg on 1/11. Swelling, pain, and weakness persisted. Seen in ER 1/15, exam with persistent weakness and lymphadenopathy. MRI brachial plexus performed which showed multiple enlarged nodes adjacent to brachial plexus. No overt inflammation or compression of brachial plexus. Received IV dexamethasone, and PO prednisone course. Finished 10d of prednisone 40mg with improvement in soft tissue edema, but still with residual weakness and pain. EMG pending. Diagnosed with brachial plexopathy secondary to compressive adenopathy from COVID 19 vaccine.

A 34-year-old non-pregnant female patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 mRNA VACCINE; Lot Number: EL0140), via an unspecified route of administration in the left arm on 18Dec2020 at 15:30 (at the age of 34-years-old) as a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. Medical history included severe dust mite allergy (based on skin test). Prior to the vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Concomitant medications included cetirizine hydrochloride (MANUFACTURER UNKNOWN), hydrocodone bitartrate/paracetamol (NORCO), ibuprofen (MANUFACTURER UNKNOWN), and ondansetron (ZOFRAN); all for unspecified indications from unknown dates and unknown if ongoing. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within four weeks prior to the vaccination. On 24Dec2020 at 10:00, 6 days post vaccination, the patient experienced anaphylactic reaction, severe chest tightness, shortness of breath, throat soreness, hoarse voice, and mouth swelling; all reported as life threatening. The events led to an emergency room visit and she was given epinephrine (EPI-PEN), methylprednisolone (SOLUMEDROL), and diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL) as treatment. The patient stated that she developed the reactions 45 minutes after she took premedications for a dilatation and curettage procedure. The premedications included ibuprofen, hydrocodone bitartrate/paracetamol, ondansetron. She stated she had taken these medications several times before and this was the first time she had this reaction. Since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. The clinical outcomes of the anaphylactic reaction, severe chest tightness, shortness of breath, throat soreness, hoarse voice, and mouth swelling were recovered on unknown dates.; Sender's Comments: Anaphylactic reactions presented as chest tightness, shortness of breath, throat soreness, hoarse voice, and mouth swelling, developed 45 minutes after premedications including included ibuprofen, hydrocodone bitartrate/paracetamol, ondansetron for a dilatation and curettage procedure and 6 days post vaccination with BNT162B2, the event therefore is most likely attributed to these premedications unrelated to the vaccine use. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

I received the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on April 6, 2021. My symptoms began 10 days later. It all started with upper back muscle aches, on the same side as the vaccine injection. On 4/21, I checked into urgent care where both my COVID-19 and influenza vaccines were negative, so I was instructed to go to the ER to be evaluated for possible meningitis. At the ER, I mentioned separately to both the doctor and a nurse that I believed my symptoms could be related to the vaccine, but they both promptly dismissed the idea and discharged me with a ?muscle ache.? For two days I was in relentless pain, which left me basically moaning and crying for hours on end. Several of my previous gymnastics injuries from when I was in my teens had resurfaced. I finished the second round of steroids last week and am experiencing the same symptoms all over again, swelling and inflammation of the knee, severe pain in the right psoas, right toe pain, severe neck aches, and sleepless nights. I wanted to avoid a third round of steroids but couldn't endure the pain and swelling and it got to the point where I could barely walk or move, so I'm back on a third course for 15 more days. She said that they told her that she was most likely having an immune response to the vaccine. Her heart rate and blood pressure came to a more normal range and everything returned to baseline. Her heart rate was 109. She was told to rotate paracetamol (TYLENOL) and ibuprofen for at least the next 24 hours and hydrate. The events fever, chills, fatigue, joint pain, bone pain, headache, swollen lymph nodes, and swelling, pain, redness and soreness at the injection site were serious due to hospitalization from 05Jan2021 to 05Jan2021. The patient was recovering from fever, chills, joint pain, headache, heart rate and blood pressure, not recovered from fatigue, bone pain, swollen lymph nodes and swelling, pain, redness and soreness at the injection site. The event swollen lymph nodes worsened. The outcome of "injection site itched a little bit" was unknown. 36 2021-03-25 anaphylactic reaction Received the vaccine at 10:40am on 3/24/2021 and felt normal. At 1:20pm anaphylaxis set in - experie... Read more
Close
Received the vaccine at 10:40am on 3/24/2021 and felt normal. At 1:20pm anaphylaxis set in - experienced tingling then tightness in throat, tongue swelled, swallowing would cause me to choke and tongue would get stuck blocking air passage. Hyperventilating began as I could not get enough air into my lungs. For 15 minutes tried drinking water and laying down to help open airways. Breathing slightly eased for 2-4 minutes and then the anaphylaxis would spike again. This happened 3x getting worse, I called my Primary Care Physician's office and was advised to go to the ER immediately. At 2:15pm I arrived at the ER and at 2:30pm I was given a 1mg shot of EPINEPHrine, and intravenous shots of diphenhydrAMINE, methylPREDNISolone, and famotidine along with oxygen. Anaphylaxis finally dissipated around 3:30pm and by 5pm I was breathing more normally. I was discharged at 7:00pm, and was feeling very energized. I was also given a prescription for an epipen incase I should have any further issues. The next morning, 3/25/2021 I woke up after 5 hours of sleep feeling extremely energized. I had a virtual doctor's appointment with my allergist, Dr. at 12:00pm. My doctor was surprised at how well I seemed to be doing and we made arrangements to do further allergy tests in 2 weeks. We came to the conclusion that I am most likely allergic to POLYETHYLENE GLYCOL. This ingredient is also in a cold medicine that I was taking in January and I was experiencing minor anaphylaxis (which I thought was due to the extreme congestion I was experiencing with the cold). It is also an ingredient (aka PEG) in an eye cream that caused a severe eczema patch under my eye in January. After my appt, at 1:30pm I went into anaphylaxis again. My throat got tingley and began to close, my tongue swelled and again was getting stuck in my throat when I attempted to swallow. I laid down and tried to get in deep breaths. My husband bought children's BENADRYL, which does not have polyethylene glycol in it, and gave me 15ml at 2:15pm. I reached out to my allergist, Dr. and updated him. He advised that I immediately take an additional 5ml of the BENADRYL. Dr. prescribed me 60mg/day Prednisone for 2 days followed by 40mg/day of Prednisone for 4 days, 40mg/day Famotidine for 2 weeks, 10mg/day antihistamine (I chose loratadine) for 2 weeks. Dr. also shared that I should have been prescribed steroids when I was discharged from the hospital, but my energetic state gave the impression I was OK. My manic energy was a result of the epinephrine, which had finally worn off 23 hours later, causing my body to begin the allergic reaction all over again. The evening of 3/25/2021 (after the first dose of 60mg prednisone, 40mg famotidine, and 10mg loratadine) and all three meals on 3/26/2021 I experienced minor anaphylaxis when I began to eat. Tightness in throat throughout the meal and lasting an additional 20 minutes following the meal. My throat has reopened after each incident on 3/26/2021 and I was able to breathe normally again.

While receiving the vaccine I felt pain and burning. That subsided after waiting the 15 minutes for monitoring. When I arrived home my arm was sore, tight, and felt swollen. I wasn't able to sleep on that side, I wasn't able to lift normal everyday items and I felt shooting pains as if I was getting injected again. I treated myself with Aleeve and iced my arm (20 mins about 3x a day) for 3 days. Symptoms still persisted. At my second dose my experience was very different from the first however, the pain from the first one still remained. I inquired if I should still feel this pain and I was told to expect soreness. At the urge of my family and coworkers I went to my doctor on 5/4 and he informed me that I have shoulder bursitis due to the poor administration of the vaccine. The person who gave it to me either went in the wrong spot, or went too deep. I am being treated with Methylprednisolone tablets (4mg 21 tabs) currently. My doctor said that if this doesn't work I would have to see an ortho and possibly need to get cortisone injections. There is no way to tell if this will heal or if I will have to live with this for the rest of my life. Poorly skilled administration of this vaccine so far has changed my life...and not for the better.

38 2021-01-26 anaphylactic reaction Within 2 minutes of receiving vaccine, patient reported experiencing throat swelling, face and lip t... Read more
Close
Within 2 minutes of receiving vaccine, patient reported experiencing throat swelling, face and lip tingling. Patient was administered diphenhydramine PO while in clinic. At this time, patient declined to be seen in the ED and was released from clinic after additional monitoring. Patient received a course of prednisone from another physician later that day. 2 days later the patient began experiencing severe abdominal pain and was seen in the ED. Labs, right upper quadrant ultrasound, and abdominal CT were within normal limits and was determined that symptoms were likely still part of COVID vaccine anaphylactic reaction. The patient was evaluated by the acute care surgery service who did not find anything concerning and was discharged home from the ED with return precautions and instructions to follow-up with primary physician. The patient follow-up with PCP and was continued on a 5 day course of steroids. The patient will not receive a second vaccine dose at this time and was referred to see an allergist for further testing.

The swelling in my hand went down enough that I was able to make a fist and grasp objects with my fingers again. I was instructed to follow up with my PCP in one week. Since returning home, I have continued to be very easily fatigued and have had some headaches, nausea, and dizziness. I continue to feel weak when walking and have some muscle stiffness when first waking from sleep. I also continue to have some intermittent episodes of numbness and tingling.

Close
I was diagnosed by my neurologist with Guillain-Barre Syndrome. 9 days after my 2nd Pfizer shot (Sunday, March 28th), I felt tingling in my feet. On Monday night I felt tingling and pain in my feet, but I was sure it was passing and said nothing since the pain was manageable at a level 2?3. On Tuesday I was getting concerned. My feet were now tingling and in pain all day, and the pain had escalated to a level 5. On Wednesday I suddenly realized that my life could effectively be over soon. The pain was at a 7-8, and I could barely get through my day. My body felt like there were tiny needles shooting electricity into me, and it felt all-consuming. It was unrelenting, and I suddenly understood why the CEO (a COVID survivor) killed himself after suffering through constant ringing in his ears. It became CRYSTAL clear how chronic pain made regular working life impossible, and I wondered how I would get by on disability and how long it would take to kick in after applying. I started panicking while focusing enough to book a doctor?s appointment for that Friday. By the end of Wednesday my calves and thighs were severely cramped, and by Thursday my eyes were tingling and my hands and arms were tingling with pain. I feared MS since it runs in my family. I was terrified and confused and made an appointment with a PCP for Friday, April 2nd.

On 1/21/21, approximately 59 hours after I received the Pfizer\BioNTech COVID19 Vaccine #2 without any immediate adverse events, I woke up in the middle of the night with subjective fevers, sweats, chills, generalized weakness with dizziness and feeling faint, nausea, diarrhea, and severe pelvic/lower abdominal pain (though I was also in the process of starting my menstrual cycle). I also vaguely noticed an erythematous rash on my chest and abdomen at that time. I took a dose of ondansetron for nausea and acetaminophen for pain. Later that morning (1/21/21), I continued to have generalized weakness, subjective fevers and chills, extreme fatigue, nausea, and a morbilliform-type rash most prominently on my torso (chest, abdomen, back) and some areas of my upper arms and thighs, as well as bright red and hyperemic palms and soles that had a prickly sensation throughout. I no longer had abdominal pain, but did have significant polyarthritis with difficulty moving my joints without pain. This included my knees, elbows, ankles, wrists, as well as fingers/hands especially. My fingers and toes felt very swollen and I had trouble putting my normal enclosed shoes on. I took ibuprofen and Tylenol during this time for symptom control. Later I added diphenhydramine, loratadine, and famotidine. These symptoms waxed and waned in intensity for at least 8 days with continued spread of rash, extreme fatigue, ongoing joint pain, and subjective fevers. The only measured fever was on 1/23/21 when I had access to a thermometer - my oral temperature was 100.7F if I recall correctly. I never had any respiratory symptoms. On 1/29/21 I saw Hospital Allergist Dr in order to participate in a research study on adverse vaccine reactions; I did not have a formally documented medical appointment with her for my medical records. By that time, my energy level was slowly improving and I was able to return to work. My arthritis symptoms had nearly fully resolved, however, my rash had gone from not particularly bothersome to very diffusely pruritic. I began to take cetirizine for symptoms instead of loratidine. In addition, the skin along my L palm began to slough and peel off, most notably in the webspaces between my thumb and index finger bilaterally and the tip of my L thumb and L ring finger. These areas of my palm had the most notable peeling and sloughing around 2/2/21 and by 2/7/21 my R palm was also peeling in similar fashion to the L. On 2/11/21, I noticed that the skin along my L sole, particularly between all five digits had begun to peel quite markedly; large connected pieces of skin were sloughing off. The sloughing on the L foot spread from between the toes and the ball of the foot to the arch and then the heel over several days. On 2/14/21, the R foot/sole began having the same findings, with large amounts of sloughing first between the toes and then extending to the ball of the foot, arch, and ultimately the heel. Some sort of foot/sole peeling continued through the final week of February 2021 and into early March.

From the onset of the reaction to the when it started to go away was around an hour. She stated that they observed her and she didn't got into anaphylactic shock or need emergent care. She stated that she filed an online report and wanted to speak to someone in person regarding her reaction and whether or not she should get the second vaccine. She stated that her physician didn't know whether she should or not and did not give her guidance on getting the second dose. The patient wanted to know if she can get the second dose. No treatment was received for the events. Outcome of the events was reported as resolved. No follow-up attempts are needed. No further information is expected
